1
00:02:14,295 --> 00:02:15,965
Champagne?

2
00:02:21,494 --> 00:02:24,655
Sorry.
Bubbles...went up my nose.

3
00:02:27,404 --> 00:02:30,050
Actually, that's not technically champagne.
That's Cava.

4
00:02:30,310 --> 00:02:33,932
It's a Spanish sparkling wine and uses 
the champenoise process.  It um...

5
00:02:36,220 --> 00:02:38,061
Nevermind.

6
00:02:40,546 --> 00:02:42,794
<i>Is it there?</i>
One porcelain vase.

7
00:02:42,982 --> 00:02:46,486
Early Ming dynasty, circa 1400
Lot 011.

8
00:02:46,827 --> 00:02:50,248
Lot 0-1-1.

9
00:02:50,533 --> 00:02:54,211
<i>And Mason?</i>
He's here and he brought a friend.

10
00:02:55,131 --> 00:02:56,896
A very big friend.

11
00:02:57,176 --> 00:03:00,892
Whatever it takes, do not
let him leave with that vase.

12
00:03:01,079 --> 00:03:02,968
Check.  Save the world, no matter what.

13
00:03:03,116 --> 00:03:04,435
As long as you don't go over budget.

14
00:03:04,470 --> 00:03:08,211
Next up, ladies and genetlemen,
a porcelain vase.

15
00:03:08,426 --> 00:03:11,854
Early Ming dynasty, circa 1400.

16
00:03:12,269 --> 00:03:15,709
May I have a starting bid of 20,000 pounds?

17
00:03:16,392 --> 00:03:19,567
20,000. Do I hear 30,000?

18
00:03:19,747 --> 00:03:22,690
<i>30,000. Thank you sir.
30,000 is the bid.</i>

19
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:26,664
<i>Do I hear 40? Looking 40...
40,000 to the lady.</i>

20
00:03:26,987 --> 00:03:29,110
30,000 is in the budget.

21
00:03:29,960 --> 00:03:32,779
I'm officially upset now, Flynn

22
00:03:33,206 --> 00:03:36,425
Oh hey, Katie...everything okay?

23
00:03:36,670 --> 00:03:39,641
We were supposed to meet for 
lunch an hour ago. Where are you?

24
00:03:40,035 --> 00:03:41,715
I...I'm still at the, uh...

25
00:03:43,355 --> 00:03:44,858
Flynn?

26
00:03:45,084 --> 00:03:47,480
I'm at the librarian convention.
The online catalog seminar ran over. 

27
00:03:47,833 --> 00:03:51,248
You know how it is. You get a bunch of 
librarians in a room talking and...

28
00:03:51,427 --> 00:03:55,543
In the last six months we that we've
been dating, you've given a hundred excuses.

29
00:03:55,774 --> 00:03:57,110
Oh come on, a hundred?

30
00:03:57,320 --> 00:04:02,697
That will be 100,000 pounds!
<i>You're always late.</i>

31
00:04:02,891 --> 00:04:05,199
<i>150?  150,000 pounds!</i>
Slow down.

32
00:04:05,751 --> 00:04:08,595
<i>You're running off to some 
convention or book club retreat.</i>

33
00:04:09,160 --> 00:04:10,504
I brought you to England.

34
00:04:10,785 --> 00:04:14,471
And since we've gotten off the plane,
you left me waiting a dozen times.

35
00:04:15,367 --> 00:04:17,840
- I have to take that...
- Don't you take that call!

36
00:04:18,287 --> 00:04:20,812
Are you trying to bankrupt us?

37
00:04:21,015 --> 00:04:23,071
I can't really talk to you right now,
Charlene, I've got Katie on the other line.

38
00:04:23,277 --> 00:04:25,556
- Is Katie writing your checks?
- Give me five minutes, okay?

39
00:04:25,782 --> 00:04:27,621
- Don't you hang up!
- Just give me five minutes!

40
00:04:27,865 --> 00:04:30,133
I have 500,000 pounds!

41
00:04:30,422 --> 00:04:33,267
<i>Flynn...Flynn?</i>
- Wait. Wait...wh..
- 500,000

42
00:04:33,527 --> 00:04:35,152
550.

43
00:04:35,454 --> 00:04:40,660
Maybe some women are okay with the wild and
unpredictable lifestyle of dating a librarian

44
00:04:41,661 --> 00:04:43,038
but I'm not.

45
00:04:43,226 --> 00:04:44,519
600. 650.

46
00:04:44,706 --> 00:04:47,738
750. 850. I have 850.

47
00:04:47,938 --> 00:04:50,025
850,000 is the standing bid.

48
00:04:50,217 --> 00:04:52,411
<i>I want someone I can depend on.</i>

49
00:04:54,621 --> 00:04:56,547
Flynn, I'm leaving.

50
00:04:56,821 --> 00:05:01,567
Don't leave. I'll meet you in 15 minutes 
in the hotel bar. 15 minutes in the hotel 
bar. Don't leave.

51
00:05:01,817 --> 00:05:03,978
Please don't let me down again, Flynn.

52
00:05:04,259 --> 00:05:06,544
One million pounds!

53
00:05:15,601 --> 00:05:19,430
Sold! To the impatient American
for one million pounds!

54
00:05:35,202 --> 00:05:36,988
Charlene?

55
00:05:41,250 --> 00:05:44,004
And...let's wait about two weeks
before cashing that check, shall we?

56
00:05:44,353 --> 00:05:50,935
Yes, such a pleasure to find somebody
who understands the unique value and 
rarity of such a fine artifact.

57
00:05:52,921 --> 00:05:54,765
What are...what are you...

58
00:05:55,669 --> 00:05:57,553
What is that?

59
00:05:58,025 --> 00:06:00,733
That is the Philosopher's Stone.

60
00:06:01,048 --> 00:06:05,082
The most powerful and famous
transmutational relic in all of history

61
00:06:06,169 --> 00:06:07,389
What does that mean?

62
00:06:07,593 --> 00:06:11,558
It means that the stone can turn
anything it touches into gold.

63
00:06:13,004 --> 00:06:15,104
Mr. Carsen, we meet again.

64
00:06:15,494 --> 00:06:19,701
Very valuable, as you can imagine, but also
quite dangerous if you're not careful.

65
00:06:20,872 --> 00:06:25,686
My Bodyguard, Mr. Percy once had the
misfortune of holding the stone

66
00:06:25,876 --> 00:06:27,992
without taking the necessary precautions.

67
00:06:28,204 --> 00:06:30,946
Well gentlemen, this is all very 
fascinating, but my girlfriend is waiting...

68
00:06:34,700 --> 00:06:37,362
I don't mean to be "heavy handed" [laughs]

69
00:06:39,055 --> 00:06:43,931
<i>Get it?
Because his hand is made of gold.</i>

70
00:06:56,212 --> 00:06:57,861
Carsen...

71
00:06:59,789 --> 00:07:02,144
I want that stone!

72
00:07:08,278 --> 00:07:10,970
- That's 18th century Korean.
- Sorry.

73
00:07:27,739 --> 00:07:30,634
British Cavalry sword.  Silver filigree.

74
00:07:30,933 --> 00:07:32,313
Bit overpriced.

75
00:07:39,860 --> 00:07:43,218
- This is rented!
- Of course it is.

76
00:07:58,754 --> 00:08:02,282
- You know you're going to lose, Flynn.
- Actually, I know two things.

77
00:08:02,487 --> 00:08:08,848
Your sword grip and tactics show me that
you're fighting with a German 14th century
sword style developed by Johannes Liechtenauer

78
00:08:09,824 --> 00:08:13,654
Defeated only by the Renaissance technique 
taught by Hutton in 1892.

79
00:08:14,082 --> 00:08:15,665
What's the other thing you know?

80
00:08:15,848 --> 00:08:19,274
The Renaissance style taught
by Hutton in 1892.

81
00:08:27,811 --> 00:08:30,141
Katie, I'm here! I know...
Excuse me, sir.

82
00:08:30,332 --> 00:08:32,798
I'm a little late.
I'm a lot late.

83
00:08:34,816 --> 00:08:37,668
Hi. I'm looking for my girlfriend.

84
00:08:37,848 --> 00:08:40,037
She has blonde hair, and she's American.

85
00:08:40,213 --> 00:08:45,402
Would she have had a lingering air of 
disappointment as if she just made a 
difficult, but necessary, decision?

86
00:08:45,585 --> 00:08:48,480
Yeah? Yeah. That's her.

87
00:08:48,669 --> 00:08:51,955
She left for the airport half an hour ago.
This is for you.

88
00:10:07,637 --> 00:10:13,893
No, no, no, no. I understand he wrote you the 
check, but he was not authorized for that amount

89
00:10:15,522 --> 00:10:18,509
Perhaps if we return the va--

90
00:10:19,554 --> 00:10:21,706
How many pieces?

91
00:10:22,644 --> 00:10:26,112
We have some very cutting-edge
glue here at the library...

92
00:10:27,846 --> 00:10:30,521
I'll call you back.
Flynn!

93
00:10:33,923 --> 00:10:37,605
- One million pounds?
- Please Charlene, not today. I'm not in the mood.

94
00:10:37,817 --> 00:10:41,184
Oh fine.  I'll just deduct it from 
your pay for the next 50 years.

95
00:10:41,382 --> 00:10:45,730
Did the auctioneer happen to mention that 
I gave him a solid gold throw pillow 
worth about 2 million pounds?

96
00:10:45,965 --> 00:10:47,242
No.

97
00:10:47,452 --> 00:10:53,328
Well, here. Rub a quarter on the Philosopher's
Stone and you get instant gold.

98
00:10:54,103 --> 00:10:58,518
What has gotten into you? We just 
do not profit from the artifacts.

99
00:10:59,313 --> 00:11:03,275
- And this tuxedo, it's a rental.
- Hi Chris. Not today Charlene.

100
00:11:15,166 --> 00:11:17,925
- Where's Judson?
- Is in the Large Collection Annex.

101
00:11:24,110 --> 00:11:26,264
We have a "Large Collections" area?

102
00:11:36,615 --> 00:11:38,592
Charlene, how big is the library?

103
00:11:39,110 --> 00:11:41,596
As big as we need it to be.

104
00:11:49,032 --> 00:11:51,669
Noah's Ark!
<i>Flynn!</i>

105
00:11:54,182 --> 00:11:55,853
<i>Flynn!</i>

106
00:11:57,237 --> 00:11:59,035
Welcome back, Flynn.

107
00:12:00,817 --> 00:12:02,549
Listen, Judson, I need...

108
00:12:03,011 --> 00:12:06,604
Judson? Judson?

109
00:12:06,829 --> 00:12:11,278
Oh, it's the Fountain of Youth.  It just 
arrived from St Augustine, Florida.

110
00:12:12,904 --> 00:12:15,539
I'm just testing it to make 
sure it's the real deal.

111
00:12:16,434 --> 00:12:17,916
Aah, that's better.

112
00:12:18,200 --> 00:12:20,376
I'd hate to go through puberty again.

113
00:12:21,515 --> 00:12:25,320
- So, did you find Philosopher's Stone?
- Yes.

114
00:12:26,640 --> 00:12:28,337
Ask him how much it cost.

115
00:12:28,556 --> 00:12:31,421
Excellent work.  Well I...
I knew you'd come through for us.

116
00:12:31,744 --> 00:12:35,321
That's why I know we can count
on you for this next job.

117
00:12:35,547 --> 00:12:38,723
Next job?
I just got back.

118
00:12:38,983 --> 00:12:42,716
We just received the Voynich manuscript
from Yale.  It's on loan.

119
00:12:43,090 --> 00:12:45,618
It has to be deciphered by morning.

120
00:12:45,836 --> 00:12:48,280
- Well, I need to leave early today.
- Oh, not today.

121
00:12:48,482 --> 00:12:50,998
Yes, today, because my personal life...

122
00:12:52,640 --> 00:12:55,872
Oh, that's right.  I'd forgotten, Monday
is your training day with Excalibur.

123
00:12:58,641 --> 00:12:59,759
He missed you.

124
00:13:00,039 --> 00:13:02,484
Well, I've already had my sword
practice for the week.

125
00:13:03,396 --> 00:13:06,235
Yeah, you're probably going to have
to spend the night, so we have a cot

126
00:13:07,538 --> 00:13:09,816
All right!  Stop it!  All of you!

127
00:13:11,008 --> 00:13:13,317
Flynn?  Are you all right?

128
00:13:13,515 --> 00:13:16,762
Yeah, I'm fine.  No, I'm good.
What could possibly be wrong?

129
00:13:17,112 --> 00:13:21,253
I mean, I work in a basement doing a
secret job I can't even tell my mother about.

130
00:13:21,635 --> 00:13:25,514
And...my best friend is a sword!
What could possibly be wrong?

131
00:13:26,322 --> 00:13:28,437
I think he's snapped.

132
00:13:29,099 --> 00:13:31,678
Flynn, you're scaring the relics.

133
00:13:31,890 --> 00:13:35,626
This place is sucking the life out of me!

134
00:13:36,572 --> 00:13:39,136
I looked around, I don't even see relics
anymore.  You know what I see?

135
00:13:39,453 --> 00:13:44,336
I see the parts of my life that I
have given up finding them!

136
00:13:44,766 --> 00:13:47,325
Blackbeard's Chest: my mom's 65th birthday.

137
00:13:47,509 --> 00:13:49,897
Da Vinci's Diary: my 10 year college reunion!

138
00:13:50,310 --> 00:13:53,010
Do you even know how often 
those come along?

139
00:13:55,457 --> 00:13:58,168
Um...10 years?

140
00:13:59,474 --> 00:14:04,647
Valentine Day with my gir...
With my ex-girlfriend.

141
00:14:06,153 --> 00:14:09,784
- Oh...The girlfriend.
- It's always about the girl.

142
00:14:11,284 --> 00:14:15,485
Do you know that since I've been 
working here, I have not been in 
a relationship with a woman

143
00:14:15,909 --> 00:14:18,137
that has lasted more than six months?

144
00:14:18,366 --> 00:14:21,826
Didn't work out with Emily, didn't work out 
with Nicole, and now, Katie dumps me.

145
00:14:22,309 --> 00:14:24,139
And I really thought that she was...

146
00:14:27,057 --> 00:14:29,072
I thought that she might be the one.

147
00:14:29,315 --> 00:14:31,369
Flynn I'm sorry, but ...

148
00:14:31,804 --> 00:14:37,657
The Librarian, it isn't just a job.
It's...it's your life.

149
00:14:38,562 --> 00:14:42,981
Librarians and relationships...
Look, maybe this will help.

150
00:14:43,943 --> 00:14:49,185
Just think of yourself as 
a celibate monk.

151
00:14:50,986 --> 00:14:53,530
- We do.
- Sounds good.

152
00:14:54,749 --> 00:14:57,727
Good pep talk.
ARE YOU INSANE?

153
00:14:58,094 --> 00:15:00,843
I am 33 years old!

154
00:15:01,162 --> 00:15:04,571
Celibate a monk?  Celibate Monk?
Excalibur...

155
00:15:06,672 --> 00:15:09,366
Do it!  Do it now!
Just get it over with.

156
00:15:09,725 --> 00:15:17,276
Flynn look, you're..uh...you're overworked.
Maybe you should...maybe you should take 
some, you know, take some time off.

157
00:15:17,452 --> 00:15:20,901
You have some vacation pay coming.
But don't get greedy.

158
00:15:27,129 --> 00:15:28,401
Vacation?

159
00:15:30,621 --> 00:15:32,708
Vacation?

160
00:15:35,069 --> 00:15:38,209
Yeah.  Okay.

161
00:15:40,186 --> 00:15:42,282
Vacation.

162
00:15:47,279 --> 00:15:49,178
Do you think he'll come back?

163
00:15:49,398 --> 00:15:52,769
He'll come back, the library 
has plans for him.

164
00:15:53,137 --> 00:15:57,149
Prince Vlad Dracul.
This is his insignia.

165
00:15:57,749 --> 00:15:59,764
Order of the dragon.

166
00:16:00,535 --> 00:16:06,307
Vlad was prince of Walachia
in the 15th century.

167
00:16:06,490 --> 00:16:08,800
He was noted to his cruelty.

168
00:16:09,024 --> 00:16:12,370
over 40,000 people were
tortured and murdered

169
00:16:12,536 --> 00:16:14,507
during his brief six year reign.

170
00:16:14,755 --> 00:16:19,640
His favorite method of execution 
was impailment on a six-foot stake.

171
00:16:20,230 --> 00:16:23,649
Hence, he earned the nickname
Vlad The Impailer.

172
00:16:23,855 --> 00:16:26,749
Was Dracul a vampire, professor?

173
00:16:27,259 --> 00:16:28,872
Vampire?  No.

174
00:16:29,897 --> 00:16:31,881
No, I don't think so.

175
00:16:32,337 --> 00:16:40,709
No.  No, the bloodlust fed the rumors 
from his enemies, and also his name is

176
00:16:40,899 --> 00:16:44,646
Dracula, meaning son of the 
dragon - son of the devil.

177
00:16:45,283 --> 00:16:48,617
But now, he's a moldering corpse somewhere

178
00:16:48,810 --> 00:16:50,691
in those mountains, I'm sure...

179
00:16:51,617 --> 00:16:54,044
...a skeleton, like any other.

180
00:16:54,225 --> 00:16:56,241
Well, that's all the time we 
have for this evening.

181
00:16:56,413 --> 00:17:01,195
We will see you this time next week.
<i>For now, be young.</i>

182
00:17:10,436 --> 00:17:14,805
I enjoyed lecture, professor.
Very informative.

183
00:17:17,723 --> 00:17:21,900
2000 years Romanian history, all they 
want to know about is the vampires.

184
00:17:23,133 --> 00:17:25,845
Dracula always was Best Seller.

185
00:17:26,612 --> 00:17:28,713
Where do I know your face?

186
00:17:28,974 --> 00:17:32,893
My work has attracted a lot
of attention lately.

187
00:17:33,063 --> 00:17:38,412
Kubichek.  You recently resigned as
Security Minister from the Russian government.

188
00:17:39,110 --> 00:17:42,328
Not as much fun as your old
days in the KGB, I suppose.

189
00:17:42,475 --> 00:17:44,648
Haven't you heard, 
there's no more KGB?

190
00:17:45,429 --> 00:17:47,794
No more Russia, really.

191
00:17:48,339 --> 00:17:55,027
That government is a sham.  I'm going 
to do something about that.  We are 
going to do something about that.

192
00:17:55,503 --> 00:17:57,165
What do you need from me?

193
00:17:57,387 --> 00:18:02,126
He wasn't in synagogue.  We found him 
much further south, in the Carpathians.

194
00:18:02,509 --> 00:18:04,302
You've found the body?

195
00:18:07,925 --> 00:18:13,234
I'd remembered we had two scrolls we had 
taken from Nazis that were in turn stolen

196
00:18:13,538 --> 00:18:18,377
from a monastary in France.  I went 
into old files and found them.

197
00:18:18,847 --> 00:18:23,312
This one is map to Dracul's body.

198
00:18:24,382 --> 00:18:28,710
And this one provides clues to 
where the French monks hid this.

199
00:18:30,996 --> 00:18:34,717
No.  No.  This is a hoax.  I've 
searched for this my entire life.

200
00:18:35,127 --> 00:18:36,752
It's real.

201
00:18:37,013 --> 00:18:39,643
And you're going to help us find it.

202
00:18:40,389 --> 00:18:42,938
The Judas Chalice.

203
00:18:46,420 --> 00:18:49,165
Flynn, open up, it's Charlene.

204
00:18:58,082 --> 00:18:59,400
What are you doing here?

205
00:19:00,165 --> 00:19:05,741
Well, my combination speed dating / 
wine tasting was two streets down.

206
00:19:06,164 --> 00:19:08,661
- How did that go?
- Here.

207
00:19:11,753 --> 00:19:14,820
This is how you spend your free
time, couped up in your apartment?

208
00:19:15,024 --> 00:19:17,545
Yeah, just catching up on some reading.

209
00:19:18,756 --> 00:19:21,269
Yeah.  You, of all people, 
don't read enough.

210
00:19:21,501 --> 00:19:25,559
I've also discovered this 
new online poker game

211
00:19:25,771 --> 00:19:27,461
which is really amazing. 
By using binomial

212
00:19:27,665 --> 00:19:31,210
coefficients and probability
theories, I've been able to 
correctly guess the cards

213
00:19:31,439 --> 00:19:32,843
73% of the time.  I have won

214
00:19:33,058 --> 00:19:36,408
over 25,000 virtual dollars.

215
00:19:36,609 --> 00:19:38,480
I'm virtually proud of you.

216
00:19:38,742 --> 00:19:42,172
You have time off.
Get out of this apartment.

217
00:19:43,627 --> 00:19:47,283
I just...I don't feel like it right now.

218
00:19:47,588 --> 00:19:52,928
Look, these are travel brochures 
for vacations I never took.

219
00:19:53,117 --> 00:19:55,002
So, don't do what I did.

220
00:19:55,182 --> 00:19:57,704
Here.  You could go to the Grand Canyon.

221
00:19:57,877 --> 00:20:00,193
You know 7 people fall off the
Grand Canyon every year?

222
00:20:00,958 --> 00:20:04,093
- Wine tasting in Sonoma.
- Wine goes bad.

223
00:20:04,402 --> 00:20:07,501
Just get out of here.  Go to 
Las Vegas.  New Orleans.

224
00:20:07,526 --> 00:20:10,009
And what if New Orleans dumps me?

225
00:20:10,325 --> 00:20:13,314
The city of New Orleans will dump you?

226
00:20:14,030 --> 00:20:21,027
I just...I don't want to get my hopes up on 
something new and then be disappointed

227
00:20:21,260 --> 00:20:23,629
And then lose.  Again.

228
00:20:24,481 --> 00:20:29,086
Look.
I'm sorry about Katie.

229
00:20:29,747 --> 00:20:34,235
But you can't get stuck,
you gotta move on to new things

230
00:20:34,385 --> 00:20:35,699
to a new someone.

231
00:20:35,859 --> 00:20:37,823
And when I lose the next someone?

