FBI, CIA?

467
00:45:00,703 --> 00:45:02,985
Why you want the Judas Chalice?

468
00:45:03,225 --> 00:45:07,718
I already have the Judas Plate.  And the Judas 
Knife and Fork.  So if I want the complete set...

469
00:45:10,161 --> 00:45:12,634
You don't know who I am?

470
00:45:12,866 --> 00:45:15,743
Sergei Kubichek, former KGB.

471
00:45:16,048 --> 00:45:19,025
Security Minister of the new Russian 
Government until six months ago

472
00:45:19,319 --> 00:45:23,551
when you resigned under the 
charges that you were...agressive.

473
00:45:24,593 --> 00:45:26,640
Democracy not working for you, Sergei?

474
00:45:26,810 --> 00:45:31,034
Chaos not working for me. Starvation.

475
00:45:31,637 --> 00:45:34,571
Well, one man can't fix it all.

476
00:45:34,754 --> 00:45:38,169
One man leading army of 
unkillable soldiers can.

477
00:45:40,688 --> 00:45:44,614
Who could stand against 
an army led by Dracul?

478
00:45:45,353 --> 00:45:50,281
- Manned by a hundred, a thousand undead.
- He's here.

479
00:45:50,977 --> 00:45:52,623
You raided the coffin?

480
00:45:52,832 --> 00:45:55,235
We are going to bring 
order back to Russia.

481
00:45:55,448 --> 00:45:59,957
We are going to rebuild Russia 
to her former glory and beyond.

482
00:46:01,494 --> 00:46:05,877
Wow.  I actually never sat this 
close to a psychopath before.

483
00:46:06,849 --> 00:46:08,515
Kill him.

484
00:46:10,330 --> 00:46:11,993
You can't kill me.

485
00:46:12,165 --> 00:46:15,038
That coin has writing on 
it over 500 years old.

486
00:46:15,431 --> 00:46:17,558
You meat heads won't 
be able to decipher it.

487
00:46:17,746 --> 00:46:20,032
I, on the other hand, 
have phD's in cryptology

488
00:46:20,227 --> 00:46:22,074
and every language 
you can imagine.

489
00:46:22,245 --> 00:46:24,809
Face it, Kubichek.
You need me.

490
00:46:26,965 --> 00:46:30,514
You don't put much faith 
in my organizational abilities

491
00:46:33,262 --> 00:46:34,706
Professor Amil Lazlo?

492
00:46:34,995 --> 00:46:38,198
- You've heard of him?
- Of course.  You're a genius.

493
00:46:38,496 --> 00:46:39,571
Thank you.

494
00:46:39,745 --> 00:46:42,138
I have read every book you've written 
on Eastern European folklore.

495
00:46:42,288 --> 00:46:43,921
I especially the synth...

496
00:46:44,060 --> 00:46:47,285
So...if I have Professor Lazlo?

497
00:46:48,484 --> 00:46:51,557
Uh, yes.  In that case, killing 
me is totally an option.

498
00:46:52,645 --> 00:46:55,088
I'm sorry, son, I had no 
choice.  They forced me.

499
00:46:59,767 --> 00:47:01,347
Make it interesting.  Have your...

500
00:47:05,376 --> 00:47:07,301
Didn't we bring more men?

501
00:47:07,509 --> 00:47:12,832
George disappeared, then Peter, then 
two others.  Drinking, maybe?

502
00:47:13,128 --> 00:47:15,896
So hard to find good help.

503
00:47:21,433 --> 00:47:26,213
Look, I get this 
from Voodoo shop.

504
00:47:27,269 --> 00:47:32,750
Datura, made from a poisonous weed known 
to cause disorientation and hallucination.

505
00:47:33,175 --> 00:47:34,654
Used in Voodoo ceremonies.

506
00:47:34,857 --> 00:47:38,462
You always talk in, like, whole 
paragraphs. You ever notice that?

507
00:47:39,088 --> 00:47:41,129
Open up.

508
00:47:48,170 --> 00:47:49,462
Get the car.

509
00:47:49,639 --> 00:47:53,213
Drug kicks in, we'll drive him into the 
river.  Make it look like an accident.

510
00:47:55,075 --> 00:48:00,474
Okay, Mr. Librarian.  What kind of fancy 
books will get you out of this one?

511
00:48:05,153 --> 00:48:07,457
Houdini and wrote books, too.

512
00:48:20,790 --> 00:48:21,417
You?

513
00:48:21,712 --> 00:48:24,753
Flynn Carsen.  I got about two minutes 
before I'm in a full blown hallucination.

514
00:48:24,919 --> 00:48:26,146
So we gotta get you outta here.

515
00:48:26,352 --> 00:48:28,978
- I just deciphered the markings...
- There's no time for tha--

516
00:48:29,577 --> 00:48:31,565
- You did?
- Yes.

517
00:48:31,764 --> 00:48:35,009
What language is it this 
time? Is it French?

518
00:48:35,044 --> 00:48:38,254
Langue d'oc.  It makes reference 
to the Vigenère cipher.  Here.

519
00:48:40,306 --> 00:48:42,584
- Find the numerical transposition...
- Yes.

520
00:48:43,362 --> 00:48:49,656
- M-E-A-L-I...
- How many combinations?

521
00:48:49,993 --> 00:48:52,553
- Ten charactors...
- Factor of 10.

522
00:48:52,712 --> 00:48:54,747
Divided by four which is 
the repeated characters

523
00:48:54,957 --> 00:48:56,826
907,200

524
00:48:57,574 --> 00:49:01,182
It's Latin.  Illuminate.
[mumbles]

525
00:49:10,152 --> 00:49:13,220
- What?  Illuminate what?
- Wait a minute.

526
00:49:14,470 --> 00:49:18,721
The tarnish on this coin.  Silver 
oxidizes, it doesn't corrode like this.

527
00:49:20,023 --> 00:49:24,001
I was so preoccupied with the writing, 
I never examined the coin itself.

528
00:49:26,877 --> 00:49:28,894
- It's glass.
- Glass.

529
00:49:29,551 --> 00:49:34,109
This isn't a coin.
This is a lens.

530
00:49:43,161 --> 00:49:44,866
Morgus Bay.

531
00:49:45,077 --> 00:49:46,539
That's where we need to go.

532
00:49:46,741 --> 00:49:50,096
God, you make one 
hell of a historian!

533
00:49:52,141 --> 00:49:54,735
Flynn? Flynn?

534
00:49:56,414 --> 00:49:58,858
I'm out of time.  We 
gotta get you going.

535
00:49:59,048 --> 00:50:00,546
Come on. Come on.

536
00:50:00,755 --> 00:50:02,230
No, no.

537
00:50:04,111 --> 00:50:06,788
My legs are too slow.
You go.  I will...

538
00:50:10,242 --> 00:50:12,441
- I'm good.
- Good luck.

539
00:50:39,509 --> 00:50:44,375
- Please help me. People are chasing me.
- Need a chaser, Bro?  PARTY!  YEAH!

540
00:51:06,847 --> 00:51:09,417
- Okay, going away.
- Get up Flynn.

541
00:51:10,348 --> 00:51:14,333
You're not going to think yourself 
out of this one, book boy.

542
00:51:29,818 --> 00:51:31,342
Where did she come from?

543
00:51:31,543 --> 00:51:35,430
- Simone?
- I leave you alone for one day...

544
00:51:35,924 --> 00:51:39,259
Now please, GO, before 
there is trouble.

545
00:51:43,091 --> 00:51:47,285
- Nicolai, shoot this tramp.
- With pleasure.

546
00:51:53,250 --> 00:51:54,786
Shoot her!

547
00:52:09,839 --> 00:52:13,143
- Flynn!
- Simone!

548
00:52:23,992 --> 00:52:26,608
- Missed.
- Didn't.

549
00:52:45,723 --> 00:52:47,237
Simone?

550
00:52:49,723 --> 00:52:52,970
Don't die.
Don't die because of me.

551
00:53:20,820 --> 00:53:24,443
- Hello?
- Hi.

552
00:53:45,425 --> 00:53:47,153
Oh good, you're awake.

553
00:53:47,390 --> 00:53:48,970
I made you some tea.

554
00:53:50,948 --> 00:53:52,702
But I saw you get shot.

555
00:53:53,290 --> 00:53:55,587
You had no pulse, 
you were dead.

556
00:53:55,772 --> 00:53:57,863
Yeah, sure, I was already dead.

557
00:53:58,855 --> 00:54:01,851
What do you mean dead?
Like undead? Like a vampire?

558
00:54:02,028 --> 00:54:07,112
Afraid so.  Tea?
Oh! That is very hurtful!

559
00:54:07,527 --> 00:54:10,321
Well, excuse me! I just woke 
up in a vampire's lair!

560
00:54:12,427 --> 00:54:14,545
You didn't...you didn't...

561
00:54:14,932 --> 00:54:17,202
I don't kill for food.

562
00:54:18,558 --> 00:54:21,306
See?
Blood.

563
00:54:22,600 --> 00:54:25,588
- Oh God.
- Check for holes.

564
00:54:34,802 --> 00:54:37,348
Kidding.  You're so uptight.

565
00:54:42,191 --> 00:54:44,633
That's early Baroque, 
about 300 years old.

566
00:54:46,436 --> 00:54:48,496
In fact, a lot of this stuff is.

567
00:54:48,714 --> 00:54:52,528
Yes, momentoes I have 
collected over the years.

568
00:54:54,674 --> 00:54:57,077
And...how old are you?

569
00:54:57,257 --> 00:55:00,895
Americans...to ask a 
lady such a question.

570
00:55:02,328 --> 00:55:04,521
I'm 403 years old.

571
00:55:06,560 --> 00:55:08,093
- 400?
- Oui.

572
00:55:08,374 --> 00:55:10,307
- And three?
- Yes.

573
00:55:10,930 --> 00:55:13,496
Well, I've dated older 
women before, but

574
00:55:14,286 --> 00:55:17,717
dead is new for me.

575
00:55:18,158 --> 00:55:21,750
Yeah, so I thought I knew a lot about 
history because I've studied it, but you

576
00:55:22,749 --> 00:55:26,125
you have actually lived it.

577
00:55:26,306 --> 00:55:31,494
- How did you ...
- I was born in Paris in 1603.

578
00:55:32,286 --> 00:55:38,678
It was a very exciting century, there 
was Galileo, Shakespeare, Rembrant,

579
00:55:38,883 --> 00:55:41,531
a thrilling time to be alive.

580
00:55:41,775 --> 00:55:46,430
And in Paris, I met Francoise.
He was a teacher at the university.

581
00:55:47,913 --> 00:55:51,632
We love and we 
were soon engaged.

582
00:55:52,090 --> 00:55:55,257
I always loved music ever 
since I was a little girl.

583
00:55:55,436 --> 00:55:59,237
And by the age of 25 I was an 
opera singer at the Royal Court.

584
00:56:10,407 --> 00:56:13,198
It was the best time 
of my life until...

585
00:56:19,668 --> 00:56:23,524
I died on June 12, 1628.

586
00:56:24,012 --> 00:56:29,157
A vampire passed his curse onto 
me, condemning my soul to 
walk the night forever.

587
00:56:30,044 --> 00:56:31,869
Never to rest.

588
00:56:32,928 --> 00:56:35,787
And Francoise?

589
00:56:36,683 --> 00:56:39,119
I never saw him again.

590
00:56:39,999 --> 00:56:43,299
My destiny took my 
love away from me.

591
00:56:44,633 --> 00:56:47,873
He did love books very much.

592
00:56:49,352 --> 00:56:52,544
I stayed on in Paris 
for another 200 years

593
00:56:52,735 --> 00:56:56,018
trying to find the 
vampire and kill him.

594
00:56:56,202 --> 00:57:02,068
But he vanished.  I learned 
about the Judas Chalice and how 
it could resurrect dead vamipires.

595
00:57:02,475 --> 00:57:05,985
With such a power, I knew the 
undead could overrun the Earth.

596
00:57:06,182 --> 00:57:07,576
You wanted to protect it.

597
00:57:07,825 --> 00:57:10,474
That's why I followed the 
trail to the monastery.

598
00:57:12,925 --> 00:57:15,535
But I couldn't decipher
the writing on the pendant.

599
00:57:15,758 --> 00:57:19,912
So I decided to stay on in New 
Orleans to protect at least 
this part of the puzzle.

600
00:57:20,391 --> 00:57:24,761
Until I saw some man studying 
the monastery and I knew that 
trouble was coming.

601
00:57:28,124 --> 00:57:31,139
That's why you appeared in my dream.

602
00:57:31,549 --> 00:57:35,019
- You were asking for help.
- From the Librarian.

603
00:57:36,114 --> 00:57:38,056
How do you know about the library?
See, that's just...

604
00:57:38,250 --> 00:57:40,222
Oh, all vampires know about the library.

605
00:57:40,457 --> 00:57:43,839
You Librarians have been around 
almost as long as we have.

606
00:57:44,176 --> 00:57:46,956
This is from before Crusades.

607
00:57:47,681 --> 00:57:52,184
It depicts the library's 
eternal battle against evil.

608
00:57:52,477 --> 00:57:55,811
More to your job than just 
saving old relics, huh Flynn?

609
00:57:57,259 --> 00:58:00,645
The symbol on the shield, 
that's the Tree of Knowledge.

610
00:58:02,615 --> 00:58:04,116
Who's the knight?

611
00:58:04,298 --> 00:58:07,475
He is known as the Scholar.
He is the greatest Librarian of them all.

612
00:58:08,036 --> 00:58:11,740
Legend has it, he built the library 
and is keeper of all of its secrets.

613
00:58:13,464 --> 00:58:16,461
He is known as Iahuda.

614
00:58:18,083 --> 00:58:25,187
That's Hebrew.  It's the Hebrew name for... 
The Hebrew name for Judson.

615
00:58:29,663 --> 00:58:33,722
The sunrise is in one hour.
I can't go out during the day.

616
00:58:33,911 --> 00:58:36,635
Simone, I need you to come with 
me.  I know where the Chalice is.

617
00:58:36,834 --> 00:58:38,591
Morgus Bay, about a half 
a day's drive from here.

618
00:58:38,779 --> 00:58:41,311
It's too far, I will never 
survive the trip in the sunlight.

619
00:58:44,060 --> 00:58:46,372
I know somebody.

620
00:58:48,540 --> 00:58:51,335
Hey, hey, Mr. professor man.
This is my cousin Earl.

621
00:58:53,661 --> 00:58:55,703
You disappeared on me 
after the big show.

622
00:58:55,894 --> 00:58:58,839
Sorry, Andre, I met some 
friends. This is the luckiest 
boat in New Orleans, huh?

623
00:58:58,997 --> 00:59:00,379
Well, I never said it was the prettiest.

624
00:59:00,549 --> 00:59:02,270
Simone, Andre.
Andre, Simone.
Cousin Earl.

625
00:59:08,607 --> 00:59:10,971
If that's the freinds 
you met, I forgive you.

626
00:59:11,520 --> 00:59:14,035
You're starting to get that 
New Orleans spirit, mon ami.

627
00:59:14,831 --> 00:59:16,456
How far to Morgus Bay?

628
00:59:16,692 --> 00:59:20,008
We should get there around 
nightfall.  But why Morgus? I 
mean, it ain't nothing but swamp...

629
00:59:20,170 --> 00:59:22,218
I'm going in the 
cabin now, Andre.

630
00:59:22,517 --> 00:59:24,995
We don't want to be 
disturbed until nightfall.

631
00:59:25,975 --> 00:59:27,795
Okay.  I get it.

632
00:59:28,073 --> 00:59:31,979
- Okay?
- I get it.

633
00:59:33,146 --> 00:59:35,864
Laissez les bon temps roulez, baby.

634
00:59:37,086 --> 00:59:39,191
Gas me up, Cous'.

635
01:00:01,159 --> 01:00:03,612
Now Morgus is a mile inside the swamp.

636
01:00:03,671 --> 01:00:07,519
Now the water is too shallow, you 
gonna have to paddle the rest from here.

637
01:00:08,734 --> 01:00:10,278
You sure about this?

638
01:00:10,473 --> 01:00:12,721
Leave the light on for us.

639
01:00:46,014 --> 01:00:47,411
Are you okay?

640
01:00:47,630 --> 01:00:50,338
- I'm fine.  Are you okay?
- Yes.  I'm fine.

641
01:00:50,462 --> 01:00:52,256
Okay.

642
01:00:53,455 --> 01:00:56,117
It's a warning.

643
01:00:57,087 --> 01:00:59,774
Somebody doesn't want 
us to go any farther.

644
01:01:04,050 --> 01:01:07,301
Oh...is that what I think it is?

645
01:01:09,033 --> 01:01:10,831
Cover your eyes.

646
01:01:24,323 --> 01:01:27,189
It's the Pride.  That's Lafitte's ship.

647
01:01:28,198 --> 01:01:30,726
See, Jean Lafitte was a 
19th century pirate, he was...
<i>Flynn...</i>

648
01:01:30,987 --> 01:01:34,219
We must be near the Barataria 
swamp.  But he used to use this

649
01:01:34,303 --> 01:01:40,026
maze of swamps as his headquarters
Flynn, I know, I was here twice when 
it was docked in New Orleans. Parties.

650
01:01:40,530 --> 01:01:42,856
- So you knew the pirate Lafitte?
- Mmm-hmm.

651
01:01:43,208 --> 01:01:45,207
Lightweight when it came to rum.

652
01:01:45,392 --> 01:01:47,867
Not so tough, passed 
out in his puffy shirt.

653
01:01:50,472 --> 01:01:52,512
Well, I guess you knew him well.

654
01:01:55,644 --> 01:02:02,513
- If I remember correctly, these stairs lead to...
- Look out!

655
01:02:05,501 --> 01:02:07,116
Trip wire.

656
01:02:08,673 --> 01:02:10,142
Would you have survived that?

657
01:02:10,392 --> 01:02:13,353
Head cut off?  As bad 
as sunlight.  I go POOF.

658
01:02:14,387 --> 01:02:15,629
Stake through the heart?

659
01:02:15,863 --> 01:02:18,165
Only wood from an 
Aspen tree will work.

660
01:02:19,279 --> 01:02:21,775
- Hey!
- Just asking.

661
01:02:24,839 --> 01:02:28,166
- This way?
- That leads to Jean's quarters.

662
01:02:29,503 --> 01:02:33,289
- You mean his bedroom, don't you?
- Now, now.  Don't be jealous.

663
01:02:52,590 --> 01:02:54,353
Well, well, well.

664
01:02:58,624 --> 01:03:03,081
The man himself,
buried with his treasure.

665
01:03:03,990 --> 01:03:06,504
I guess you can take it with you.

666
01:03:10,812 --> 01:03:13,401
That's just...nasty.

667
01:03:14,780 --> 01:03:16,377
Combination lock.

668
01:03:16,571 --> 01:03:19,294
It'll be opened with 
the right six letters.

669
01:03:19,491 --> 01:03:21,702
- Clue is in...
- French?

670
01:03:24,989 --> 01:03:30,027
The faith was breached, 
the mark was sealed.

671
01:03:30,796 --> 01:03:36,343
- Faith was breached?
- The mark was sealed.
- Um, violation, deception, betrayal

672
01:03:36,742 --> 01:03:39,103
A betrayal, sealed with a kiss.

673
01:03:39,932 --> 01:03:44,763
You see, Judas signaled the Romans 
and sealed Christ's fate with a kiss.

674
01:03:45,116 --> 01:03:47,461
- And in French, kiss is...
- Un baiser.

675
01:03:54,630 --> 01:03:56,104
- Ready?
- Yes.

676
01:03:57,718 --> 01:03:59,444
A little help.

677
01:04:17,479 --> 01:04:19,481
The Judas Chalice.

678
01:04:20,345 --> 01:04:22,428
Holy Grail for vampires.

679
01:04:23,384 --> 01:04:25,229
I thought it would be bigger.

680
01:04:25,687 --> 01:04:28,890
Anticlimactic after all this treasure.

681
01:04:35,194 --> 01:04:38,030
Wow.  This stuff is like 
catnip for you guys, huh?

682
01:04:38,515 --> 01:04:40,987
You know, I think that 
we should go now.

683
01:04:42,732 --> 01:04:44,440
Kind of a shame, really.

684
01:04:44,739 --> 01:04:46,900
Can't take the whole 
thing back with us.

685
01:04:47,196 --> 01:04:50,432
This would make a wonderful addition 
to the Large Collection Annex.

686
01:04:50,893 --> 01:04:53,134
They could put it right 
next to Noah's Ark...

687
01:04:53,370 --> 01:04:58,499
15 men on a dead man's chest.
Yo ho ho and a bottle of rum.

688
01:04:59,608 --> 01:05:02,198
I really must thank you for 
finding the Chalice for me.

689
01:05:02,385 --> 01:05:04,441
Old man said you did all the work.

690
01:05:06,076 --> 01:05:07,710
Professor?

691
01:05:08,339 --> 01:05:11,895
I have looked for this my 
whole life, son.  I had to see it.

692
01:05:15,987 --> 01:05:17,667
You.

693
01:05:24,470 --> 01:05:30,042
Old man warned me about you.
I thought it was all nonsense 
but better safe than sorry.

694
01:05:30,250 --> 01:05:32,405
Kubichek, if you hurt her I swear I'm...

695
01:05:32,868 --> 01:05:34,935
You'll what?

696
01:05:35,489 --> 01:05:38,429
Take away my
library card?

697
01:05:42,215 --> 01:05:45,638
I'd originally planned to 
resurrect Vlad on Russian soil

698
01:05:46,644 --> 01:05:51,646
But tomorrow we begin with America.
Build up nice little army...

699
01:05:51,816 --> 01:05:54,926
You don't know what you're doing.
You're unleashing a monster!

700
01:05:55,450 --> 01:05:59,603
You would know what sort of monster. 
How long since you last fed?

701
01:06:02,916 --> 01:06:04,506
Lock them in.

702
01:06:04,725 --> 01:06:07,598
Let them rot together for eternity!

703
01:06:08,247 --> 01:06:10,958
Or until hunger gets better of her.

704
01:06:27,540 --> 01:06:29,190
Flynn, are you okay?

705
01:06:29,375 --> 01:06:35,734
My eye really hurts.  This door's made out of
iron, these walls are 6 inces of wood, and 
it's about 20 hours 'til they resurrect Vlad.

706
01:06:36,425 --> 01:06:38,837
Okay, Simone, do your thing.

707
01:06:42,329 --> 01:06:43,903
I could do that.

708
01:06:44,108 --> 01:06:48,222
I'm sorry Flynn, I'm too weak,
I haven't fed in over 24 hours.

709
01:06:49,842 --> 01:06:54,137
Okay, well don't get any ideas.  You 
just sit right over here and relax.

710
01:07:01,684 --> 01:07:03,365
I can't believe this.

711
01:07:03,710 --> 01:07:09,258
After centuries trying to protect the 
Chalice, I failed.  And I led them here.

712
01:07:09,452 --> 01:07:11,364
Well, technically, I led them here.

713
01:07:11,569 --> 01:07:16,000
But it's not over yet.  For a 403 year old 
woman, you sure don't have a lot of patience.

714
01:07:21,213 --> 01:07:23,236
This looks promising.

715
01:07:25,941 --> 01:07:28,949
Newton's third law.
I've got an idea.

716
01:07:41,299 --> 01:07:46,158
Potassium nitrate.  Perfect.

717
01:08:00,886 --> 01:08:03,326
- Flynn, there are no cannon balls.
- We don't need them.

718
01:08:04,366 --> 01:08:05,199
Newton's third law?

719
01:08:05,519 --> 01:08:08,366
Every action has an equal 
and opposite reaction.

720
01:08:09,076 --> 01:08:11,742
The explosion should be strong 
enough to drive this cannon back

721
01:08:11,938 --> 01:08:15,092
- and through that door.
- Should?

722
01:08:15,293 --> 01:08:18,667
Well...like about 60% of 
the plans I come up with 

723
01:08:19,058 --> 01:08:22,787
there is a strong possibility that it 
could all go horribly, horribly wrong.

724
01:08:23,780 --> 01:08:26,716
We could die in the explosion.

725
01:08:29,622 --> 01:08:32,938
- Well I can't die.
- Right, so I'm the only one who 
could die in the explosion.

726
01:08:35,690 --> 01:08:37,981
Glad we clarified that.

727
01:08:38,969 --> 01:08:41,276
- Okay.  Here we go.
- Wait.

728
01:08:42,584 --> 01:08:44,106
For luck.

729
01:08:46,571 --> 01:08:48,074
Here goes nothing.

730
01:08:49,747 --> 01:08:51,213
Wait, wait, wait...

731
01:08:59,379 --> 01:09:01,778
Yay Newton!

732
01:09:06,811 --> 01:09:08,366
Andre!

733
01:09:14,868 --> 01:09:16,446
Andre!

734
01:09:19,229 --> 01:09:21,680
He's been hit from behind.  See 
if you can go start the boat.

735
01:09:22,640 --> 01:09:24,419
Andre?

736
01:09:32,008 --> 01:09:34,727
Simone!  No, no, no!
Stop the boat!

737
01:09:34,944 --> 01:09:37,502
I'm sorry, Flynn, but 
you can't come with me.

738
01:09:38,502 --> 01:09:40,206
Simone, what are you doing?

739
01:09:41,267 --> 01:09:42,975
Simone!

740
01:09:44,188 --> 01:09:47,599
Your girl done stole 
my cousin's boat.

741
01:09:48,171 --> 01:09:51,290
- Thought you said this boat was lucky?
- It is.  For her.

742
01:10:31,617 --> 01:10:34,090
- This is my cousin Horace.
- I'm not complaining.

743
01:10:47,716 --> 01:10:50,295
Just talked to Earl, the boat's 
back at the dock, safe and sound.

744
01:10:50,851 --> 01:10:53,932
Well, looks like you got an 
honest girl, there.  For a thief.

745
01:10:54,553 --> 01:10:56,807
- Thanks.
- You need anything else?

746
01:10:58,340 --> 01:11:02,524
Don't suppose you can help me 
find a plantation house being 
rented by a bunch of Russians?

747
01:11:02,777 --> 01:11:05,958
Well, there are a lot of plantation 
houses in New Orleans.  Uh, can't 
you tell me anything else?

748
01:11:06,316 --> 01:11:09,881
No.  I don't really remember 
much from my visit there.

749
01:11:10,188 --> 01:11:13,342
What, you been there already?
Well, what you need me for?

750
01:11:13,801 --> 01:11:17,242
Look, I know you got the photographic 
memory in that head of yours.

751
01:11:17,619 --> 01:11:19,312
I got faith in you.

752
01:11:21,155 --> 01:11:26,569
- Thanks, Andre.
- Bonne chance, Mr. professor man. C'mon, Cous'

753
01:12:43,615 --> 01:12:44,964
Surprise!

754
01:12:48,505 --> 01:12:49,853
That went better in my head.

755
01:12:50,077 --> 01:12:52,225
What are you doing here?
You shouldn't be here.

756
01:12:52,432 --> 01:12:54,846
Why?  So I won't see 
you steal the Chalice?

757
01:12:55,172 --> 01:12:57,491
- To become all powerful?
- You don't understand.

758
01:12:57,699 --> 01:12:59,932
I understand.  You betrayed me.

759
01:13:00,544 --> 01:13:03,353
- You want the Chalice for yourself.
And I thought you cared about...
- I do care.

760
01:13:05,145 --> 01:13:08,256
Get back!  I'll use 
this if I have to.

761
01:13:10,584 --> 01:13:15,403
Flynn, I left you at the dock 
because I was trying to protect you.

762
01:13:15,966 --> 01:13:21,922
Well, we got you got here again.  Honestly, 
we're not this good.  You two kind of 
suck at sneaking around.  Bring them.

763
01:13:31,986 --> 01:13:33,599
Just in time.

764
01:13:33,837 --> 01:13:37,757
I am sure Vlad Dracul will 
be starved when he's awake.

765
01:13:37,965 --> 01:13:39,414
You're making a big mistake, Kubichek.

766
01:13:39,650 --> 01:13:42,501
Let's see.  Open coffin.

767
01:13:50,985 --> 01:13:53,052
What's next, old man?

768
01:13:53,279 --> 01:13:55,819
Blood must be spilled into 
the Chalice, and then

769
01:13:56,051 --> 01:13:59,798
poured on the corpse at 
the stroke of midnight.

770
01:13:59,984 --> 01:14:04,046
Let's give Dracul a 
taste of his dinner.

771
01:14:21,388 --> 01:14:25,342
It's working.
IT'S WORKING!

772
01:14:38,724 --> 01:14:44,106
Rise from the dead, warrior prince!
Rise and do my bidding!

773
01:14:53,811 --> 01:14:55,750
This can't be!

774
01:15:01,124 --> 01:15:03,952
You crippled fool!

775
01:15:04,515 --> 01:15:08,586
It was all a hoax!
I kill you!

776
01:15:22,003 --> 01:15:23,596
Lazlo?

777
01:15:25,778 --> 01:15:28,536
- Lazlo is a vampire?
- I recognized him at the ship.

778
01:15:28,814 --> 01:15:31,142
He was the one I was 
trying to protect you from.

779
01:15:33,459 --> 01:15:35,829
The one who made me.

780
01:15:50,032 --> 01:15:52,132
We've got to get that 
Chalice away from him.

781
01:15:58,149 --> 01:16:00,725
You look for you missing men, Ivan?

782
01:16:01,093 --> 01:16:03,413
Sorry, I had to snack 
on the journey.

783
01:16:03,641 --> 01:16:06,031
You killed my men, Lazlo!

784
01:16:06,381 --> 01:16:08,567
Please call me Vlad.

785
01:16:08,906 --> 01:16:10,103
If you're Vlad, who's that?

786
01:16:10,405 --> 01:16:12,708
It's a peasant in a box.

787
01:16:12,943 --> 01:16:19,422
I have lived for centuries among you humans 
unnoticed until dead cattle got sick.  Cholera.

788
01:16:19,676 --> 01:16:21,120
1829 pandemic?

789
01:16:21,269 --> 01:16:22,656
- Flynn?
- I'm sorry.

790
01:16:23,010 --> 01:16:28,793
I drank infected blood, and I was trapped 
in this withering body.  Until now.

791
01:16:28,999 --> 01:16:32,722
You wanted the Chalice for a 
cure.  To revive your powers.

792
01:16:32,993 --> 01:16:35,576
Lucky for me, Kubichek
found the first clue.

793
01:16:35,746 --> 01:16:39,133
- Not so lucky for Kubichek.
- Well, I wouldn't say that.

794
01:16:40,322 --> 01:16:45,248
Now that I have the Chalice, 
I will summon my children

795
01:16:45,553 --> 01:16:49,399
and they will drink and we will 
plunge your world into darkness.

796
01:16:49,872 --> 01:16:53,677
Come child.  Join us. 
Drink and be strong.

797
01:16:55,864 --> 01:16:57,682
Simone?

798
01:17:11,762 --> 01:17:13,135
Never!

799
01:17:13,339 --> 01:17:15,996
You destroyed my life!

800
01:17:16,169 --> 01:17:18,089
Then die with others.

801
01:17:19,668 --> 01:17:21,179
Feed!

802
01:17:23,273 --> 01:17:25,829
You got a plan, book boy?
I'd love to hear it.

803
01:17:26,000 --> 01:17:28,936
I'll take that.
Cover your eyes.

804
01:17:47,737 --> 01:17:49,712
Go get the Chalice!

805
01:17:57,056 --> 01:17:59,645
I know you're out here, Vlad!

806
01:18:02,474 --> 01:18:04,314
It's no use!

807
01:18:06,697 --> 01:18:08,478
Show yourself!

808
01:18:17,026 --> 01:18:20,639
I think it's only fair to warn you 
that I am, in fact, a Librarian.

809
01:18:22,299 --> 01:18:24,765
I've fought evil in many forms.

810
01:18:26,490 --> 01:18:30,445
Approximately 35 forms.
Give or take.

811
01:18:31,626 --> 01:18:34,561
So you have every 
reason to be afraid.

812
01:18:37,479 --> 01:18:39,710
Is that supposed to frighten me?

813
01:18:41,953 --> 01:18:44,684
'Cause mission accomplished.
Good job.

814
01:18:49,426 --> 01:18:53,272
Go! Help the Librarian!
Leave him to me!

815
01:19:13,423 --> 01:19:16,337
You follow a vampire into 
the woods at night?

816
01:19:17,268 --> 01:19:19,640
I thought you were a smart boy.

817
01:19:20,143 --> 01:19:22,650
I'm officially in trouble now.

818
01:19:28,280 --> 01:19:32,184
You Librarians break so 
easily. But tasty.

819
01:19:32,336 --> 01:19:36,042
You took my life away from me, 
but you don't get to take his.

820
01:19:36,250 --> 01:19:37,918
I gave you a gift!

821
01:19:38,083 --> 01:19:40,799
Allow me to repay favor!

822
01:20:01,781 --> 01:20:06,604
Join us Ivan, we can still 
restore order to Russia.

823
01:20:08,245 --> 01:20:12,900
I think it's time we try to pay the 
bill for what we've already done.

824
01:20:13,963 --> 01:20:17,653
- For Russia, old friend!
- Noooooooo!

825
01:20:33,473 --> 01:20:38,499
Populus tremuloides.
Populus tremuloides!

826
01:20:59,209 --> 01:21:02,399
I'm sorry for your pain, my child.

827
01:21:02,691 --> 01:21:07,140
But, as they say, the more tortured 
the vine, the sweeter the fruit.

828
01:21:07,328 --> 01:21:09,716
Vlad Dracul!

829
01:21:21,453 --> 01:21:23,908
Because I control
the Judas Chalice.

830
01:21:24,389 --> 01:21:26,468
So I control you.

831
01:21:26,734 --> 01:21:30,518
You stupid boy, that's 
not how it works.

832
01:21:32,675 --> 01:21:35,061
- Wrong move.
- Wrong hand.

833
01:21:37,093 --> 01:21:39,931
Populus tremuloides.  The aspen tree.

834
01:21:40,177 --> 01:21:43,543
Tree original tree that killed the 
original vampire, Judas Iscariot.

835
01:21:43,758 --> 01:21:48,940
Son, you make one hell of a historian.

836
01:22:16,506 --> 01:22:19,160
Simone, I want you to come 
back to New York with me.

837
01:22:19,650 --> 01:22:25,663
I mean, you already know everything about the 
Library, so I could show it to you.  I've never 
been able to share it with anybody before.

838
01:22:26,167 --> 01:22:29,302
I'm sorry, Flynn, I can't.
It's time for me to go.

839
01:22:29,724 --> 01:22:32,502
- What? Back to France?
- You did it, Flynn.

840
01:22:32,738 --> 01:22:35,067
You killed the vampire who made me.

841
01:22:35,252 --> 01:22:37,964
My soul can be at rest 
now, I can be at peace.

842
01:22:38,174 --> 01:22:41,133
Rest?  What, you mean die?
No, no, no, no, no.

843
01:22:42,230 --> 01:22:44,798
I already thought I lost you once, 
I'm not gonna go through that again.

844
01:22:44,980 --> 01:22:46,702
It's all right, Flynn.

845
01:22:48,633 --> 01:22:50,456
I want this.

846
01:22:50,935 --> 01:22:53,873
I've lived long enough, 
I made every day count.

847
01:22:54,102 --> 01:22:57,567
But we could be together.
There is a way.

848
01:23:17,600 --> 01:23:20,364
You have to stay, 
and be the Librarian.

849
01:23:20,988 --> 01:23:24,669
You have to fulfill your destiny 
as I have fulfilled mine.

850
01:23:25,269 --> 01:23:28,924
Please Flynn, sometimes 
saying goodbye is...

851
01:23:30,963 --> 01:23:33,219
The right thing to do.

852
01:23:36,223 --> 01:23:39,076
You know, there is one thing 
you can do for me, though.

853
01:23:40,619 --> 01:23:43,538
I've always wanted to 
see the sun rise again.

854
01:23:45,154 --> 01:23:47,112
Will you watch it with me?

855
01:24:10,113 --> 01:24:12,054
It's beautiful.

856
01:24:25,229 --> 01:24:31,247
I loved you, Flynn.
For a little while.

857
01:24:35,473 --> 01:24:37,256
I loved you.

858
01:24:43,178 --> 01:24:48,253
- Goodbye Simone.
- Goodbye Flynn.

859
01:26:10,643 --> 01:26:12,269
I have something for you.

860
01:26:12,491 --> 01:26:15,843
- We did not authorize any...
- It's a thank you gift.

861
01:26:23,209 --> 01:26:24,579
It's beautiful.

862
01:26:24,797 --> 01:26:27,897
Early 1800's.  Made 
by French Monks.

863
01:26:28,920 --> 01:26:31,009
There's writing on it. 
What does it say?

864
01:26:31,199 --> 01:26:32,554
Latin.  Says: Even into her night..

865
01:26:35,284 --> 01:26:38,698
Says: Follow your dream.

866
01:26:41,082 --> 01:26:43,886
And where did you dream lead you?

867
01:26:45,080 --> 01:26:47,176
Home.

868
01:26:52,585 --> 01:26:56,301
- We're still not paying for any 
unauthorized funds for any...
- I know.

869
01:27:13,160 --> 01:27:16,098
Oh, that's mine.

870
01:27:18,743 --> 01:27:22,351
Well, Flynn, you've come 
through for us once again.

871
01:27:23,333 --> 01:27:26,201
I'm just sorry we 
ruined your vacation.

872
01:27:26,411 --> 01:27:29,294
- I wouldn't say "ruined".
- Oh.  Oh good.

873
01:27:30,111 --> 01:27:36,396
So have you decided on, you know, 
whether you're going to stay on 
as the Librarian or not?

874
01:27:36,863 --> 01:27:40,007
Someone very special told me 
I should embrace who I am.

875
01:27:40,752 --> 01:27:42,526
I think she was right.

876
01:27:42,731 --> 01:27:47,608
Then we won't... [clears throat]
we won't have anymore of those...

877
01:27:47,839 --> 01:27:50,393
- Meltdowns?  No.
- Good. 'Cause

878
01:27:51,040 --> 01:27:55,224
Charlene was thinking 
about changing the locks.

879
01:28:01,026 --> 01:28:02,946
I know who you are.

880
01:28:04,458 --> 01:28:05,533
What?

881
01:28:09,594 --> 01:28:12,502
Come on Judson, I know that 
you're over 2000 years old.

882
01:28:12,977 --> 01:28:17,570
And know that the library is pitched in 
a larger battle between good and evil.

883
01:28:23,577 --> 01:28:25,454
- Iahuda.
- Yahoo to you, too.

884
01:28:25,908 --> 01:28:29,360
Flynn, I won't disagree that there 
is a battle between good and evil 

885
01:28:29,693 --> 01:28:34,125
and right now it seems like 
evil is winning. But soon,

886
01:28:34,297 --> 01:28:40,669
you and the library are going to play an 
even more important role in that struggle.

887
01:28:41,123 --> 01:28:51,921
And, as far as my being 2000 years old, 
that's...well, that's just insulting.

888
01:28:57,920 --> 01:28:59,220
Yeah.  Yeah.

889
01:29:01,804 --> 01:29:03,141
Okay.

890
01:29:04,406 --> 01:29:06,899
Yeah, I guess it is kind of 
silly when you think about it.

891
01:29:08,627 --> 01:29:11,502
Scholar.  The tree of knowledge. [laughs]
